docs.abstract: Activists praised the murder indictment of Sgt. Hugh Barry as fulfilling a promise by the Bronx district attorney to fully investigate the killing of Deborah Danner in October.
docs.snippet: Activists praised the murder indictment of Sgt. Hugh Barry as fulfilling a promise by the Bronx district attorney to fully investigate the killing of Deborah Danner in October.
docs.lead_paragraph: A week after a New York City police sergeant shot and killed a woman who had a mental illness in her apartment last October, the Bronx district attorney, Darcel D. Clark, summoned more than two dozen members of the clergy and other community leaders to her office and urged them to give her a chance to investigate the case fully and to hold off on protests.

headline.main: Officer’s Indictment Makes Good on Prosecutor’s Plea for Patience
headline.print_headline: For Bronx, Officer’s Indictment Makes Good on Prosecutor’s Plea for Patience

docs.abstract: Facing a television landscape more competitive than ever, OWN and BET have added creative ambition to their business models.
docs.snippet: Facing a television landscape more competitive than ever, OWN and BET have added creative ambition to their business models.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Queen Sugar” wasted no time announcing its boldness. Debuting on the Oprah Winfrey Network last September, the very first scene of the series opened with a tight shot of Nova (Rutina Wesley) in bed. She was an image of African-American beauty rarely seen on television — flowing dreadlocks, a tattooed arm, and lean and muscular legs — while the cool tone of the lighting enhanced the richness of her dark brown skin.

headline.main: A ‘Queen Sugar’ Rush Heralds a ‘Silver Age’ for African-American TV
